(20, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'MATHS CUE (25-29)', '<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">25.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></strong><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">PRIME NUMBER:</span></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 90.3846%;\" border=\"1\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 100%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">We note, 2 = 1 <span style=\"color: #343a40; background: white;\">&times; 2, 3 = 1 &times; 3, 5 = 1 &times; 5, 7 = 1 &times; 7, 11 = 1 &times; 11. So each of the numbers 2, 3, 5, 7&hellip; has <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">two and only two factors</strong> (see #23). They are 1 and itself. <span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Such numbers are called Prime Numbers.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; color: #343a40; background: white;\">Note:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; color: #343a40; background: white;\"> 1. The smallest Prime Number is 2, which is the only even prime number.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; color: #343a40; background: white;\">2. They are all Composite Number. However, Composite Numbers can be written as a product of Prime Numbers, which is unique except for the order. This property of Composite.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; color: #343a40; background: white;\"><span style=\"mso-spacerun: yes;\">&nbsp;</span>3. All numbers have at least two factors, they are 1 and itself. However, numbers which have more than two factors are called <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">COMPOSITE NUMBERS. </strong>So,<strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"> </strong>besides 2, other even numbers has at least 2 as their third factor, as such even numbers, other than 2, cannot be Prime Numbers.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; color: #343a40; background: white;\">4. </span><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Of the two numbers, both of which are not prime, if 1 is the only common factor among them then they are called <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">CO-PRIME</strong> numbers. The H.C.F. (See #28) of co-prime numbers is always 1. So, if we determine the H.C.F. of two numbers and find that it is I, certainly those are co-prime numbers.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">For examples: 20 and 21.Noneofthemareprime numbers, except for1 they do not have any common factors. As such they are called CO-PRIME NUMBERS, or simply <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">CO-PRIMES</strong>.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">27.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></strong><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">PRIME FACTORISATION:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">: .30=2x3x5. We understand that any whole number can be expressed as a product of its prime factors, which is unique except for the order. This is the <strong>FUNDAMENTAL THEOREM of ARITHMETIC,</strong> founded with proof by the Greek Mathematician, <strong>EUCLID&nbsp;</strong>(see# 32). who lived around 300 BC. This process of factoriastion is called <strong>prime Factorisation of a number,&nbsp;</strong>or simple <strong>Prime Factorisation Method.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><strong>28. H.C.F.:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Factor (See#23) of 12 are 1,2,3,4,6,and 12. Factors of 18 are 1,2,3,6,9,and 18. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Here , the common factors of 12 and 18 are 1,2,3, and 6. Of these, the highest is 6.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong> As such,6 is the H.C.F of 12 and 18.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Means to obtain H.C.F of two or more numbers</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">(i) As explained above</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">(ii) <strong>Short Division Method:</strong> To find the H.C.F OF 12 and 18</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; STEP-1: We being with the smallest prime factor (See # 26),</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; here 2, to divide both 12 and 18.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; STEP-2: We now divide the quotients so obtained by the next </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; higher prime factor, here 3, divides both 6 and9</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;STEP-3: We continue the process until the quotients so obtained hace no common&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">divisor other than 1. Here, the quotients obtained have no commmon divisor or factor save 1.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; STEP-4: The H.C.F is the product ot the common divisors of the given numbers.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Here, both the numbers have the common divisor 2 and 3. besides 1.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; So, their H. C.F =2X3-6</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">(iii) Euclid\'s Method or long Division Method: We start by dividing the larger number by the smaller one.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ---- 12 being the smaller number. is the divisor and 18 is the dividend&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ------ The remainder (if any), here 6, divides the first divisor, here 12.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ------- The remainder is zero. The process of dividing the preceding&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;divisor by the remainder carries on, so long there remains no&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;remainder, i.e. the remainder is zero.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The last divisor is the H.C.F of the given numbers. If the given numbers exceed two,in such case we obtain the H.C.F of the first two smaller numbers and continue the process with the H.C.F&nbsp; so obtained wirh the next higher number. This process is continued till all the numbers are exhausted. Finally, the H.C.F so obtained is the desired result.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">(iv) Prime Fatorisation Method (See #27):</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">The product of the common prime factors (see #26) is the H.C.F.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Here, the common prime factors are 2 and 3, which are encireled.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; So the H.C.F = 2X3=6</span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Note: G.C.D,&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">i,e, Greatest Common Divisor and G.C.M, i,e Greatest Common Mesure are the other names of H.C.F. Some authors use the abbreviation H.C.M, i,e. Highest Common Measure instead of H.C.F.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">29.L.C.M:</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Multiples of 2 are 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12.........Multiples of 3 are 3, 6, 12, 15, 18,.....We note, the common multiples of 2 and 3 are 6, 12, 18....Of the common multiples of 2 and 3, we observe 6 is the lowest.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong> So the L.C.M of 2 and 3 is 6</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Means to obtain L.C.M of two or more numbers,</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp;</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; i)&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">As shown above. That is, by writing a good number of multiples, beginning with the smallest multiple so that at least two or three</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; commmon multiples could be noted. In the expamle, shown above,the first three common multiples are 6, 12 and 18, the lowest&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; being 6 is the L,C,M of 2 and 3.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>&nbsp; ii) Short Division method:</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;To find the L,C, M of 12, 18,20&nbsp;<strong> STEPS TO FOLLOW</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</strong>Arranging the given number in ascending order, as shown. Then we begin to divide each of the numbers by&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;thir common prime factor (See #26).&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;This process is continued until the quotients so obtained are either 1 or numbers which have no common&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; factor between them other than1.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">Now, the L.C.M is the product of all the divisors together with the last quotients so obtained , These last qootients have no common divisor or fatcor, except 1, or each of the quotients could be 1, if not all.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;the L,C,M =2X2X3X1X3X5=180</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong> &nbsp;iii) Prime Factorisation Method (see #29):</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\"><strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>12 = 2X2X3</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 18 = 2X3X3</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 20 = 2X2X5</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; the L,C,M = 2X2X3X3X5= 180</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-family: \'times new roman\', times, serif;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The L.C.M is the product of as many distinct prime factors available. Here, we obtained two 2\'s , two 3\'s and single 5. So the&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; L.C.M = 2X2X3X3X5= 180.</span></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
INSERT INTO `content` (`id`, `subject_id`, `paper_id`, `chapter_id`, `question_id`, `content_name`, `content_details`, `status`, `create_by`, `create_date`, `update_by`, `update_date`) VALUES
(21, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'MATHS CUE (10-13)', '<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">10.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></strong><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">ADDITION:</span></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 96.0044%;\" border=\"0\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 50%;\"><col style=\"width: 50%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Two and three together makes five.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Symbolized, 2 + 3 = 5</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">We read, <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">&ldquo;2 Plus 3 is 5&rdquo;</strong>. We add 3 with 2 get 5.</span></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Note:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\"> 2 and 3 are called <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Summands</strong> or <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">Addends</strong>. 5 is called the <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">sum</strong> of 2 and 3.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">The result of addition is Sum.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">11.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></strong><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">SUBTRACTION:</span></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 96.7814%;\" border=\"0\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 50%;\"><col style=\"width: 50%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\"></td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">5 is lessen by 3. The result is 2.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Symbolized, 5 - 3 = 2</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">We read, <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">&ldquo;5 minus 3 is 2&rdquo;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">We subtract 3 from 5 get 2.</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraphCxSpLast\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">Note:</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\"> 5 is called <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">MINUEND</strong>, 3 is called <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">SUBTRAHEND </strong>and 2 is the<strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"> DIFFERENCE, some say, remainder.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">12.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></strong><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">MULTIPLICATION:</span></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 85.3496%;\" border=\"0\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 100%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: right;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">7 + 7+ 7+ 7+ 7 = 35. This process of repeated addition can be re- written as 7 <span style=\"color: #343a40; background: white;\">&times; 5 = 35. This means five 7&rsquo;s are added. In other words, 7 increases by 5 times. To read <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">&ldquo;7 multiplied by 5 is 35&rdquo;</strong>.</span></span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; color: #343a40; background: white;\">The result of multiplication is called &ldquo;product&rdquo;.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"margin-left: 1.0in; mso-add-space: auto; text-align: justify; text-indent: -.25in; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><!-- [if !supportLists]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif; mso-fareast-font-family: \'Times New Roman\';\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">13.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt \'Times New Roman\';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span></strong><!--[endif]--><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">DIVISION:</span></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"border-collapse: collapse; width: 79.7511%;\" border=\"0\"><colgroup><col style=\"width: 100%;\"></colgroup>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\"></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">35 - 7 = 28, 28 - 7 = 21, 21 - 7 = 14, 14 - 7 = 7 and finally 7 - 7 = 0. We understand 35 contains five 7&rsquo;s. This process of repeated subtraction can be expressed as 35 - 7 = 5. This means 35 is divided into 7 equal parts, so that each part is 5. To read <strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\">&ldquo;35 divided by7 is 5&rdquo;.</strong> </span></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align: justify;\"><strong style=\"mso-bidi-font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\">The result of division is called &ldquo;Quotient&rdquo;.</span></strong><span style=\"font-size: 12.0pt; line-height: 107%; font-family: \'Times New Roman\',serif;\"> (See# 19)</span></p>', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
